"attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Percy was born in 1457, in Leconfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with William Jackson. She died on 27 July 1485, in Beverley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1457–27 July 1485":"1457–27. juuli 1485","1437–1505":"1437–1505","1470–1571":"1470–1571","1457–1485":"1457–1485","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","27 July 1485":"27. juuli 1485","1485":"1485","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1505":"1505","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Horbling, Lincolnshire, England":"Horbling, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leconfield, Yorkshire, England":"Leconfield, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1457–27 July 1485":"1457–27. heinäkuuta 1485","1437–1505":"1437–1505","1470–1571":"1470–1571","1457–1485":"1457–1485","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","27 July 1485":"27. heinäkuuta 1485","1485":"1485","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1505":"1505","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Horbling, Lincolnshire, England":"Horbling, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Leconfield, Yorkshire, England":"Leconfield, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1457–27 July 1485":"1457–27 juillet 1485","1437–1505":"1437–1505","1470–1571":"1470–1571","1457–1485":"1457–1485","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","2